full_text: eh dude feet on the grounda lot of people aint fans in california. it depends on the area, my town of like 3,500 people has a lot of teslas maybe 1/6 vehicles but if i go to 2/3 surrounding towns thhat number drops to maybe 1 in 50 and im not even trying to troll here.. a lot of people blame teslas for our ongoing energy chrisis (they shut down the san onofre boobies which didnt help) and high cost of electricity.. i know kinda sensless? i live in rural north county san diego. a lot of people also blame tesla for accelerating this green trend.. ill be at work and people will be blaming elon musk because 2 stroke weed wackers are becoming illegal. mostly though people blame you for the phasing out of older gas vehicles in california i dont know why  but you definitely accelerated that timeline. also a few of my friends are truckers and they are not a fan. then there are the environmentalists. maybe if you showed more footage of your mines and how your batteries are sustainably sourced and recyclable people would have less stones to throw.. oh also people in europe are getting tired of the surveillance state and everyone is pretty sure once we are all in electric vehicles tey will be able to limit our freedumb more especially if something like a social credit score is ever adopted. sometimes the road is plaid with good intentions<3

There is now a letter of confession from the "Vulkan Group". State security is investigating. Berlin. Production at the Tesla plant in Gr√ºnheide near Berlin has come to a standstill following a power failure. A spokeswoman for the US electric car manufacturer confirmed on Tuesday that a fire at a nearby electricity pylon had led to a power cut. The plant had been evacuated. A burning electricity pylon had previously caused the power outage in the region in eastern Brandenburg near Berlin. Numerous households were also affected at times. At midday, the "Volcano Group", which is classified as left-wing extremist, claimed responsibility for an "attack on the power supply" as a protest against the US car manufacturer. "We sabotaged Tesla today," the group said in a letter on Tuesday. A spokesperson said on Tuesday that the police had received the letter of confession. Its authenticity is being checked. The authorities are currently assuming arson, and the state security department of the State Office of Criminal Investigation has begun an investigation. "If the initial findings are confirmed, this is a perfidious attack on our electricity infrastructure," Brandenburg's Interior Minister Michael St√ºbgen (CDU) had previously announced on Tuesday. "This will have consequences. Thousands of people have been cut off from their basic supply and put in danger." "Volcano group" is said to have previously carried out an attack Tesla went on to say that all measures had been taken to secure the production facilities. After consultation with the electricity provider Edis, Elon Musk's company does not expect production to restart quickly. The "volcano group" was already suspected of carrying out an arson attack on the power supply to the Tesla construction site in 2021. At the time, they accused Tesla of being neither green, ecological nor social on the radical left-wing website https://t.co/BonnrAMGj8. The Brandenburg Office for the Protection of the Constitution wrote about the letter of confession in its 2021 report. It also stated: "In recent years, left-wing extremists have repeatedly carried out arson attacks in Berlin as "volcano groups"." Since last week, environmentalists have been protesting against the expansion of the site in Gr√ºnheide, on which Tesla wants to build a freight station and logistics and storage halls and which is partly located in a water protection area. Since Thursday, around 80 to 100 activists have been occupying part of the state forest that Tesla wants to clear in the event of an expansion. The majority of the population of Gr√ºnheide, a community of 9,000 inhabitants, recently spoke out against the expansion plans in a survey. The site in question is around 120 hectares in size. full_text:
When we attended in 2021 we spent a good 4 hours touring the factory (yes we're geeks) and speaking with as many local people (albeit in poor German / English) as possible and they all loved Tesla. Maybe Tesla refused the negative people from attending (not sure how they would know) or maybe it's just a tiny minority that actually are negative about the factory... The fact remains that the trees planted around this factory were planted to be cut down... you can tell as they were all planted in neat rows and extremely close to one another which forces them to grow tall quickly which makes them ideal for making things from.

If this was a petrol chemical factory or a new BMW factory for petrol cars I'd understand it but it's a factory producing electric cars which can be charged from sun or wind power and are infinitely better for the environment than petrol and diesel cars ü§∑‚Äç‚ôÇÔ∏è

Oh and Tesla are planting 3x the number of trees (albeit 60+ miles away)...
